[1] India (West Bengal)
Date: Thu 2 Oct 2008
Source: The Statesman [edited]
<http://www.thestatesman.net/page.arcview.php?date=2008-10-02&usrsess=1&clid=23&id=251796>


[In West Bengal] 2 cases of dengue were reported from Birbhum's
Chinpai and Bakreswar today [2 Oct 2008]. A 40-year-old man from
Birbhum's Chinpai village was admitted to Suri Sadar hospital on
Tuesday [30 Sep 2008] after he complained of symptoms similar to
dengue. He is now under treatment in Suri Sadar Hospital. Another
patient, a 32-year-old woman, a resident of Bakreswar Thermal Power
Project Township, was admitted to the Suri Sadar hospital with
symptoms of dengue. She was shifted to the Kolkata Medical College
and Hospital today [2 Oct 2008].

--
Communicated by:
Dr Satadal Das, MD, DCP
Consultant Microbiologist
Peerless Hospital & BK Roy Research Centre
76 Satyen Roy Road
Kolkata 700034
India
<drsatdas@hotmail.com>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Das for forwarding the article that mentioned
these dengue cases. Although 2 dengue cases hardly constitute an
outbreak, their occurrence is interesting as they happened in the
midst of a chikungunya virus outbreak reported in this same article
(see ProMED archive no. 20081002.3112).

This illustrates the essential role of laboratory diagnosis to
distinguish which viruses are being transmitted in a situation like
this one where clinical presentations may be similar.

A map of India showing the location of West Bengal state can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/india_pol01.jpg>
and a map of West Bengal state showing the location of Howrah
District, where these cases occurred, can be accessed at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howrah_District>
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of India can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?g=1270396&v=22.9,79.6,5>. - Mod.TY]

