[2] Pakistan (Punjab)
Date: Sat 5 Oct 2008
Source: The International News [edited]
<http://www.thenews.com.pk/print1.asp?id=139371>


The National Institute of Health, Islamabad has confirmed as many as
11 persons infected with dengue virus up to Saturday [5 Oct 2008], of
which 10 belong to Basal village while one was from Thatta village in
tehsil Jand. [A tehsil is an administrative division that consists of
a city or town that serves as its headquarters, and may contain
additional towns, and a number of villages. - Mod.TY]

"We have so far sent more than 200 blood samples of dengue fever
suspects from 4 high-risk villages of tehsil Jand to the NIH
(National Institute of Health) for confirmatory tests," said district
health officer [DHO] Attock Dr Sultan Mehmood Khan, while talking to
'The News' Saturday [5 Oct 2008] , added that the surveillance teams
are still busy on prevention and control of the infection in the area.

Confirmation of 8 positive cases within one week in tehsil Jand of
district Attock had convinced health officials to believe in
recurrence of the dengue fever outbreak, as the confirmation of cases
proved the existence of mosquito causing infection [transmitting the
virus] in the area. The DHO office has established 4 medical camps
one each in village Basal, village Thatta, village Bomail, and Pind
Sultani for checking up suspects of the disease. "The camps remained
operational during Eid holidays," claimed Dr Sultan adding nearly 700
persons with high fever have gone under medical examination at the 4
camps within past 4 days. "We have received results of nearly 175
cases from the NIH so far of which only 11 have been tested
positive," he said adding his office has yet to receive final reports
in some 25 cases. "It seems as the situation is well under control
now as on Friday [4 Oct 2008] after examining some 200 persons with
fever, we found only 6 suspects of dengue fever and sent their blood
samples to the NIH."

He said the downward trend of occurrence of the infection might be
the result of fogging in the high-risk areas. "2 rounds of fogging
have already been performed in the 4 high-risk towns," he said while
responding to a query adding his office would ensure a total of 5
sessions of fogging in the areas for prevention of the disease.

Dr Sultan added that the medical camps established in the 4 towns
would be operational till elimination of the infection from the area.

[Byline: Muhammad Qasim]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Fogging may provide temporary reduction of adult _Aedes_ vectors of
dengue virus, but will not provide longer-term control. Reduction in
mosquito breeding sites is required for that. Since a relatively
small proportion of the febrile cases were confirmed as due to dengue
virus infection, one wonders what the etiologies were for the
majority of the patients.

A map of Pakistan showing Punjab province can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/pakistan_pol_2002.jpg>
A map and other information for Attock district in north Punjab can
be accessed at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attock_District>.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Pakistan can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?g=1184248&v=30.310,71.330,5> - Mod. TY

