[3] Singapore
Date: Thu 2 Oct 2008
Source: Bloomberg [edited]
<http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601081&sid=agFUHgCCzh70&refer=australia>


According to a report in the New England Journal of Medicine that
exposes a vulnerability in the nation's blood supply, 3 people
contracted the potentially lethal dengue virus from a blood donor in
Singapore last year [2007].

Scientists led by Paul Tambyah at the National University of
Singapore said in the report, 2 men, aged 64 and 72, suffered fever,
muscle pain and fluid build-up in their chests after receiving blood
donated by a 52-year-old man. A 3rd man, 74, was infected without
suffering any symptoms. All 3 were discharged from hospital in good
health, the report said.

Dengue, the world's most common mosquito-borne disease, is endemic in
Singapore, where it has infected more than 4600 people this year
[2008]. The flu-like illness strikes about 50 million people annually
worldwide and leads to about 500 000 hospitalizations, mostly
children, according to the World Health Organization (WHO). At least
2.5 percent of patients die.

"Although screening is expensive, confidence in the blood supply
could outweigh cost-effectiveness considerations,'' Tambyah and
colleagues wrote in a letter to the journal's editor.

Singapore doesn't screen blood donors for dengue because available
tests would take 4 weeks, rendering blood platelets that must be used
within 5 days useless, Tan Hwee Huang, deputy division director of
blood supply at the Health Sciences Authority, said in a 30 Sep
[2008] telephone interview.

Singapore's Health Sciences Authority rejects blood donors showing
symptoms of dengue, and asks those who may have been exposed to defer
giving blood, according to the authority. It also removes blood
donations from people subsequently diagnosed with an infection or who
show symptoms.

The infected blood came from a repeat donor who gave blood in July
last year [2007], the report said. He later told the blood bank he
had a fever the day after the donation, prompting an investigation.
The 3 men who were subsequently infected were being treated for
diseases including diabetes, hypertension, heart disease, kidney
failure, and cancer.

[Byline: Simeon Bennett]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[This is an interesting case where the blood donor was viremic but
not yet showing symptoms of dengue virus infection, so he was not
rejected as a donor.

ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett also forwarded this story.

A Health Map/ProMED interactive map of Singapore can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=1.4,103.8,6>. - Mod.TY]

