[5] American Samoa
Date: Sat 4 Oct 2008
Source: The International Herald Tribune (IHT), Associated Press (AP)
report [edited]
<http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/10/04/america/AS-American-Samoa-Dengue.php>


Health officials in American Samoa say there were more confirmed
cases of dengue fever reported in the US territory in September
[2008] than in all of 2007.

The Department of Health says the 115 cases of the mosquito-borne
disease brought the total number so far this year [2008] to 162,
compared with 109 last year [2007]. One person, a 10-year-old boy,
died of the disease this year.

The department is urging residents to clean areas where mosquitoes breed.

American Samoa is located 2300 miles (3700 kilometers) south of Hawaii.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[On 29 Sep 2008 Radio New Zealand International
<http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=3Dread&id=3D42263> &id=3D42263>
reported that Samoa's Ministry of Health is predicting a drop in the
number of dengue fever cases this month. As of the third week of 27
Sep [2008] 57 people had the virus compared with 219 in July and 281
in August. The ministry however is concerned that not all cases being
treated are being reported by doctors.

[Maps showing the location of American Samoa in the South Pacific can
be accessed at
<http://www.graphicmaps.com/webimage/countrys/oceania/as.htm>
and the Health Map/ProMED interactive map at
